    "revise": "You are the FIGURE REVISER (Opus) for \"The LLM Stack\". Chapter: content/13-interp-safety-gov/01-mechanistic-interpretability.md\nThe chapter's core intuitions: The residual stream is an additive shared bus: every attention/MLP sub-layer reads from it and ADDS back, so the value at any layer is embedding + sum of all prior contributions, and any downstream quantity (a logit, an attention score) decomposes linearly into per-component contributions. Attention moves information ACROSS positions; the MLP processes WITHIN a position.; Superposition: a model wants far more features than it has dimensions, so it packs n >> d_model sparse features as non-orthogonal (almost-orthogonal) directions, exploiting the fact that only a few fire per token. The unavoidable price is polysemantic neurons - a single neuron responds to a mix of unrelated features - which is why you cannot read a network neuron-by-neuron.; Probing and the logit lens are OBSERVATIONAL: probing shows whether a feature is linearly decodable at a layer; the logit lens unembeds an intermediate residual to show the prediction sharpening across depth. Both measure correlation/presence, not use - you must intervene to claim causation.; Activation patching turns correlation into cause: run the corrupted input but inject one clean activation (denoising = is it sufficient?) or the reverse (noising = is it necessary?), and measure recovery to localize behavior to a (layer, position, component). Factual recall shows a two-site early(subject-MLP)/late(final-token-attention) pattern.\n\nReview each of these figures (the ones this chapter just drew/edited):\n  mechinterp-superposition-geometry, mechinterp-residual-stream-bus\n\nFor EACH: render and SEE it \u2014 `python3 scripts/preview_fig.py <NAME> --theme both` from /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook,\nthen view /tmp/figpreview/<NAME>.light.png and .dark.png. Judge strictly:\n  - Does it actually BUILD INTUITION for its concept (not just decorate)? Is it correct vs the chapter?\n  - Theme-safe (no hardcoded primary color; readable in BOTH light and dark)?\n  - Nothing clipped by the viewBox; no illegible overlaps; no tofu glyphs (ASCII only in the SVG)?\n  - Marker present in the chapter exactly once; figcaption has a bold lead + takeaway?\nIf a figure has ANY problem, FIX it: Edit /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/figures/<NAME>.html (and re-render to confirm), or\nfix a missing/duplicate marker in the chapter. Re-verify after fixing.\n\nSet verdict per figure: good / fixed / still-broken / missing. `passed` = every figure good-or-fixed\nAND present. Return the structured object."
