    "revise": "You are the FIGURE REVISER (Opus) for \"The LLM Stack\". Chapter: content/07-inference-serving/14-multi-tenant-lora-serving.md\nThe chapter's core intuitions: Merging a LoRA collapses the model to ONE adapter; multi-tenancy requires keeping the LoRA path SEPARATE so a single batch can serve many adapters at once (merging or per-adapter passes wreck the batch).; The batched problem is a grouped/segmented matmul: one shared base GEMM plus a per-row low-rank correction where each row may use a different A,B,r,alpha. Sorting the batch by adapter makes each adapter's rows contiguous (a segment), so its weight tile is loaded once and reused across the segment.; The low-rank parenthesization y = W0 x + (alpha/r) B(Ax) shrinks d_in -> r then expands r -> d_out and never materializes BA: ~99% of FLOPs are the base GEMM, ~1% the LoRA correction.; In decode the LoRA correction is bandwidth-bound, not FLOP-bound: many distinct adapters' weights are each streamed to serve only a few token-vectors, so it can be <1% of FLOPs yet a ~20-30% bandwidth tax; fusing the gather so each tile loads once is what makes it affordable.\n\nReview each of these figures (the ones this chapter just drew/edited):\n  sgmv-segmented-gather-matmul\n\nFor EACH: render and SEE it \u2014 `python3 scripts/preview_fig.py <NAME> --theme both` from /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook,\nthen view /tmp/figpreview/<NAME>.light.png and .dark.png. Judge strictly:\n  - Does it actually BUILD INTUITION for its concept (not just decorate)? Is it correct vs the chapter?\n  - Theme-safe (no hardcoded primary color; readable in BOTH light and dark)?\n  - Nothing clipped by the viewBox; no illegible overlaps; no tofu glyphs (ASCII only in the SVG)?\n  - Marker present in the chapter exactly once; figcaption has a bold lead + takeaway?\nIf a figure has ANY problem, FIX it: Edit /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/figures/<NAME>.html (and re-render to confirm), or\nfix a missing/duplicate marker in the chapter. Re-verify after fixing.\n\nSet verdict per figure: good / fixed / still-broken / missing. `passed` = every figure good-or-fixed\nAND present. Return the structured object."
